WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:13.800
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. This is a series&nbsp;
on the foundations of mathematics, and currently,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:20.280
we're investigating elementary calculus from the&nbsp;
point of view of polynomials or poly numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:27.330
This is a novel and much-simplified approach to&nbsp;
the subject. In our last video, we had a look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.330 --> 00:00:35.280
at linear and quadratic polynomials or poly&nbsp;
numbers and their associated graphs. Today,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.280 --> 00:00:42.300
we're going to carry on talking especially about&nbsp;
parabolas or quadratic polynomials in more detail.

00:00:42.300 --> 00:00:50.940
So, let's summarize what we accomplished in&nbsp;
the last few slides of the last video. We're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:50.940 --> 00:00:57.810
talking about a quadratic polynomial; there&nbsp;
it is—P equals just a list of numbers: a, b,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.810 --> 00:01:06.060
and c, or in standard alpha form, a plus b alpha&nbsp;
plus c alpha squared. Now, we're assuming this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:13.020
is really a quadratic polynomial, so that this&nbsp;
term here, this c constant, is actually nonzero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.020 --> 00:01:21.720
so it really is degree two. We discovered by&nbsp;
expanding the Taylor by poly number that the first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:30.600
derivative or the first sub-derivative was b plus&nbsp;
2c alpha, and the second sub-derivative was c. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.600 --> 00:01:38.400
also determined that the tangent line or the first&nbsp;
tangent to the poly number at the point r is given&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:49.170
by this expression. So, that's a line—a degree&nbsp;
one polynomial—unless this is zero, which is an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.170 --> 00:01:59.070
approximation to the poly number P at the point r.&nbsp;
r is just some random number, and we're generally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.070 --> 00:02:03.960
working over the rational numbers here, but a lot&nbsp;
of what we say works for the integers as well.

00:02:06.210 --> 00:02:08.850
At this point, we can observe&nbsp;
something reasonably interesting:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.510 --> 00:02:18.510
the slope of the tangent line to P at r is&nbsp;
exactly the derivative of P evaluated at r. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.510 --> 00:02:25.230
we saw last time that when we had a line like&nbsp;
this, the two constants here had geometrical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.230 --> 00:02:32.850
significance. This was the y-intercept,&nbsp;
and this was the slope. This quantity here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.850 --> 00:02:40.020
b plus 2c r, is exactly what you get when you&nbsp;
take the derivative and evaluate it at r. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:46.770
this gives us a geometrical interpretation of what&nbsp;
the derivative or the first sub-derivative means:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:56.790
it is the slope of the tangent line to the&nbsp;
poly number or polynomial at the point r. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.790 --> 00:03:00.720
for different points r, there are different&nbsp;
tangent lines, and those tangent lines will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:07.110
have different slopes, and the slope at&nbsp;
every point r is given by the derivative.

00:03:07.110 --> 00:03:14.880
A useful deduction to make from that is this&nbsp;
theorem here: that the tangent line is horizontal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:24.570
precisely when r has the value minus b over 2c.&nbsp;
Now, that's an immediate consequence of setting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:24.570 --> 00:03:32.070
the derivative, which is b plus 2c r, equal to&nbsp;
zero and solving for what r must be. This is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.070 --> 00:03:36.210
linear equation, so when we set it equal to&nbsp;
zero, we are guaranteed to have a solution:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.210 --> 00:03:45.570
it's minus b over 2c. This number is, as we'll&nbsp;
see, very important in terms of the geometry of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:45.570 --> 00:03:54.210
the parabola for the quadratic polynomial. And we&nbsp;
can see that another way by doing something that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.210 --> 00:04:00.540
we've already talked about in a former video in&nbsp;
this series. If you look at Math Foundations 48B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:06.180
we talked about completing the square in a&nbsp;
quadratic expression. We're going to do that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:15.330
now with this quadratic polynomial a + b alpha&nbsp;
+ c alpha squared. I must warn you that our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.330 --> 00:04:20.310
notation here is different from what it was there.&nbsp;
This is a sort of non-standard notation; we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.310 --> 00:04:27.850
indexing our coefficients with a, the constant&nbsp;
term, and c, the coefficient of alpha squared.

00:04:27.850 --> 00:04:33.220
Alright, so what we're going to do is&nbsp;
we're going to rewrite this thing here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:33.220 --> 00:04:37.450
first of all by taking out a common&nbsp;
factor c, which we're assuming is nonzero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.450 --> 00:04:47.440
writing it as c times (alpha squared + b/c times&nbsp;
alpha + a/c). Then, in this expression here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:55.120
we're going to add this term and also subtract&nbsp;
it so that nothing actually has changed. Where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:55.120 --> 00:05:01.600
did this term come from? Well, it's exactly half&nbsp;
of this coefficient here, so we're taking half&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:08.590
of this coefficient here and squaring it, and&nbsp;
then also subtracting it as well. The reason&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.590 --> 00:05:13.780
why we're doing that is because now these first&nbsp;
three terms here are actually a perfect square.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:13.780 --> 00:05:22.480
This thing here is c times (alpha + b/2c) squared.&nbsp;
The reason is simply that when we square this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:29.050
we're gonna get alpha squared, we're gonna&nbsp;
get b/2c squared, and twice the product will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.050 --> 00:05:35.920
give us b/c times alpha—the thing that's right&nbsp;
there. Of course, there's also the other terms:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:44.020
when we take them outside the bracket, multiply c&nbsp;
by a/c, we get a, and when we multiply it by minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.020 --> 00:05:54.070
b squared over 4c squared, we get minus b squared&nbsp;
over 4c. I'll write that just a little bit more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.070 --> 00:06:01.540
compactly by taking this constant business over&nbsp;
a common denominator of 4c. So, we get (4ac - b&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:09.760
squared) all over 4c as the constant term there&nbsp;
and c times (alpha + b/2c) all squared there.

00:06:14.170 --> 00:06:18.790
Now we make a simple but important&nbsp;
observation that whenever we have a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.790 --> 00:06:25.780
square, that square is necessarily&nbsp;
positive. When I say positive,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.780 --> 00:06:31.390
I generally mean greater than or&nbsp;
equal to zero. So, this term here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.390 --> 00:06:39.580
if we substitute alpha for r, any number, then&nbsp;
r + b/2c all squared will always be positive.

00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:46.540
So, I've repeated that formula that we've just&nbsp;
obtained; we've rewritten the polynomial P in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:46.540 --> 00:06:53.170
this fashion here. It's the same polynomial,&nbsp;
it's just been rewritten. And now we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.170 --> 00:06:58.810
deduce some important things, so we'll put these&nbsp;
together in a theorem: three different statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.810 --> 00:07:08.590
The first is that if c is positive, then P(r) is&nbsp;
bigger than or equal to this number for any r,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.590 --> 00:07:18.400
with equality happening here precisely&nbsp;
when r happens to be minus b over 2c. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:18.400 --> 00:07:22.780
this is an inequality. If there was an&nbsp;
equal sign, it would be an equality,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.780 --> 00:07:27.310
and when we have an inequality like this,&nbsp;
it's telling us this is always bigger than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.310 --> 00:07:31.180
or equal to this. It's usually interesting to&nbsp;
ask, well, what about the special case? When&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.180 --> 00:07:37.570
exactly are they actually equal? Because that's&nbsp;
included here as a possibility. So, this second&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.570 --> 00:07:42.610
part of the statement is telling us that the&nbsp;
equality occurs precisely when r has this value.

00:07:42.610 --> 00:07:49.480
Let's just have a look at that statement first:&nbsp;
that's an immediate consequence of this. Because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:57.430
if c is positive, then this is positive, and&nbsp;
we've just observed that this quantity here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:57.430 --> 00:08:04.060
is always positive, so this is a positive thing.&nbsp;
And so, if we add it to this, we're always going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:10.600
to get something which is bigger than or equal&nbsp;
to this. That's the statement there. The value&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:10.600 --> 00:08:19.060
of the poly number, or the polynomial at r, is&nbsp;
always at least this number here. And when do we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:19.060 --> 00:08:23.800
actually get equality? Well, we get equality&nbsp;
when this term is actually equal to zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.800 --> 00:08:32.230
and this will be equal to zero precisely&nbsp;
when the value r here satisfies r + b/2c&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.340 --> 00:08:45.430
equals zero—in other words, when r equals minus b&nbsp;
over 2c. That's illustrated by this picture here.

00:08:45.430 --> 00:08:54.490
Okay, so here's a picture of such a&nbsp;
quadratic polynomial where c is positive,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.490 --> 00:09:00.370
so it opens up like this. We say it's a&nbsp;
parabola opening upwards, and here's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.370 --> 00:09:07.960
value minus b over 2c. The function's value at&nbsp;
that will be exactly this, because this term&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:15.130
will be zero. So, there's the value (4ac - b&nbsp;
squared)/4c right there. And geometrically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:15.130 --> 00:09:20.920
you can also see that the parabola is opening&nbsp;
up—it's always bigger than or equal to this value,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:20.920 --> 00:09:28.000
and it attains this value exactly when x equals&nbsp;
this number here. That's what we're saying. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.020
this number here is exactly the same quantity&nbsp;
that appeared in our previous theorem, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:39.850
stated that this tangent line here—the tangent&nbsp;
to the polynomial at this point—is horizontal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.850 --> 00:09:48.670
which is a standard kind of important fact in&nbsp;
calculus: that when you have a minimum here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.670 --> 00:09:54.280
the minimum is characterized by the tangent&nbsp;
being horizontal. That's what we're seeing here.

00:09:54.280 --> 00:10:01.150
So, the second part of the theorem is what happens&nbsp;
when c is strictly negative. If c is less than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:01.150 --> 00:10:09.520
zero, then the claim is that P(r) is less than&nbsp;
or equal to this quantity for any r, and again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:16.690
equality happens exactly in the same situation&nbsp;
when r equals minus b over 2c. And that's again&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:16.690 --> 00:10:22.660
a consequence of this formula because if this&nbsp;
term here is now negative—less than zero—and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:22.660 --> 00:10:28.300
this is always positive, then the product will&nbsp;
still be negative, and so we're always going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:28.300 --> 00:10:34.060
get here as a total something which is less than&nbsp;
or equal to this because it's this plus something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:34.060 --> 00:10:40.360
negative. So, it's always going down, and it&nbsp;
doesn't go down—we have equality precisely when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:40.360 --> 00:10:44.980
this is zero. And that's the same condition&nbsp;
as previously, when r is minus b over 2c.

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:51.370
So, the picture that goes with that is this&nbsp;
one here. It's a parabola opening downwards;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:51.370 --> 00:11:00.700
there's the critical point minus b over 2c.&nbsp;
At that point right there, the value of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:00.700 --> 00:11:07.540
polynomial is (4ac - b squared)/4c, and for&nbsp;
all other values, it's something less—the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.540 --> 00:11:17.200
value is less. And again, that's the place where&nbsp;
the tangent is horizontal, the slope is zero.

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:23.710
And there's a third part of the&nbsp;
theorem: that the line x equals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.710 --> 00:11:32.470
minus b over 2c is an axis of symmetry of&nbsp;
the parabola. So, in this picture here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.470 --> 00:11:38.560
what we're talking about is this line here, the&nbsp;
line where x happens to be this critical value,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:42.670
or over here, this line here. And the&nbsp;
claim is that it's an axis of symmetry,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:42.670 --> 00:11:47.920
and that means that if you take any point on&nbsp;
the parabola here and you reflect it an equal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:52.990
amount on this side over here, you still get&nbsp;
a point on the parabola, and conversely. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:52.990 --> 00:11:57.130
it's like a mirror—if you put a mirror here, then&nbsp;
the parabola would be reflected on itself. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.130 --> 00:12:05.530
it's completely symmetrical in that line—it's&nbsp;
called an axis of symmetry. And why is that? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:05.530 --> 00:12:14.380
it's again because of this expression here: that&nbsp;
if you take any point where you, say, go r to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:14.380 --> 00:12:20.680
coordinates, so if you have some value x here so&nbsp;
that you're adding r to minus b over 2c, then this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:20.680 --> 00:12:26.560
quantity here will just be r. On the other hand,&nbsp;
if you go r in the opposite direction, then this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:33.070
quantity will be minus r, and the reason why the&nbsp;
two values are the same is because r squared and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:33.070 --> 00:12:42.160
minus r squared are equal. That's the reason&nbsp;
why the curve is symmetrical about this line.

00:12:42.160 --> 00:12:50.290
So, this is a very nice and important formula&nbsp;
in the study of the geometry of a parabola or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:50.290 --> 00:12:58.390
that quadratic polynomial. There's another very&nbsp;
interesting and important consequence to this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:58.390 --> 00:13:05.110
basic formula that we've established. There's&nbsp;
the polynomial P, and there it's rewritten after&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:05.110 --> 00:13:12.010
having completed the square. So, the consequence&nbsp;
of this is that we can actually say something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:12.010 --> 00:13:20.650
about what the shape of such a graph is. The&nbsp;
point is that the graph of P—or a graph for P,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:20.650 --> 00:13:27.190
perhaps we should say because there's no unique&nbsp;
graph—can be obtained from the graph of Q&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:27.190 --> 00:13:35.950
equals alpha squared, which is the simplest&nbsp;
quadratic polynomial, by doing three things:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:35.950 --> 00:13:42.370
by first scaling in the y-direction by some&nbsp;
constant c—actually the same c here that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:42.370 --> 00:13:52.090
here—then translating by b/2c to the left, and&nbsp;
then by translating up by (4ac - b squared)/4c.

00:13:52.720 --> 00:14:06.010
So, why is that? Well, suppose we take the&nbsp;
polynomial alpha squared, if we perhaps that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:12.580
right there and picture it right there—that's the&nbsp;
standard parabola, usually y equals x squared in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:12.580 --> 00:14:18.280
x-y terms. And it goes through the point (1, 1),&nbsp;
it goes through the point (2, 4), of course, it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:25.960
goes through the point (0, 0)—it's symmetric along&nbsp;
the y-axis. That's your basic parabola. So, if we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:25.960 --> 00:14:33.880
take that thing and we scale it by multiplying it&nbsp;
by c, what happens? Well, of course, it depends on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:33.880 --> 00:14:42.820
what c is. But let's say c happens to be, say, 2.&nbsp;
Okay, so that means that instead of plotting (1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:42.820 --> 00:14:48.490
1), we would plot (1, 2). Instead of plotting (2,&nbsp;
4), we would plot (2, 8), and so on. So, all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:48.490 --> 00:14:57.010
y-coordinates would be times 2. The parabola&nbsp;
would then look more constrained like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:57.010 --> 00:15:09.070
but it would be basically a rescaling of this one.&nbsp;
Okay, so that's one step—scaling, multiplying by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:09.070 --> 00:15:13.720
c has this effect. On the other hand, if c&nbsp;
happened to be, say, between 0 and 1, then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:13.720 --> 00:15:17.290
the effect would be sort of the opposite—it would&nbsp;
be more like going from here to here. The parabola&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:17.290 --> 00:15:23.590
would become wider, and if c was negative, well,&nbsp;
it would have then again yet a different aspect,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:23.590 --> 00:15:27.790
because then you'd be multiplying by minus&nbsp;
1, so the parabola, instead of opening&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:27.790 --> 00:15:32.890
upwards like this, would be opening downwards like&nbsp;
this—that's the effect of multiplying by minus 1.

00:15:33.430 --> 00:15:42.010
So, after that rescaling, then what happens&nbsp;
if we replace alpha with alpha + b/2c? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:42.010 --> 00:15:46.360
the effect is that instead of having things&nbsp;
centered here at zero, it's now moved over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:46.360 --> 00:15:55.690
to be centered at minus b/2c. So, for example,&nbsp;
if b/2c happened to be positive, then we would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:55.690 --> 00:16:04.210
be moving in this direction here. And why is that?&nbsp;
The probably simplest way of seeing that is to ask&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:04.210 --> 00:16:10.840
yourself what happens if we evaluate this as at&nbsp;
minus b/2c? If we evaluate this at minus b/2c,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:11.440 --> 00:16:17.620
then we get zero, then we get just the same thing&nbsp;
as we get if we evaluated this at zero. So, this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:17.620 --> 00:16:22.150
thing evaluated there is the same as this thing&nbsp;
evaluated there, so it means that the whole thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:22.150 --> 00:16:29.050
is shifted over so that its vertex is now at this&nbsp;
point. Of course, this point doesn't have to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:29.050 --> 00:16:35.140
here—it could be on the right-hand side, it could&nbsp;
be anywhere along the axis. Okay, it's starting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:35.140 --> 00:16:40.690
to look a lot like our formula now. We just have&nbsp;
to do one more thing: we have to add this, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:40.690 --> 00:16:47.920
this is some number that's independent of r, and&nbsp;
the effect of it is simply to take the values and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.920 --> 00:16:56.140
add this number to them. So, if this number was 5,&nbsp;
for example, then the graph would just be obtained&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:56.140 --> 00:17:01.420
from taking this and adding 5 to the y-coordinates&nbsp;
of all the points. So, it effectively just moves&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:01.420 --> 00:17:07.120
it up 5, or if this was minus 3, the effect would&nbsp;
be to subtract 3 from all the y-coordinates,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:07.120 --> 00:17:13.900
so the effect would be to move it down 3. So,&nbsp;
you're actually moving it up by a certain amount.

00:17:16.300 --> 00:17:24.490
Alright, so that's a proof of this claim, and&nbsp;
what it tells us is that all parabolas more or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:24.490 --> 00:17:30.460
less have the same shape. Well, in a sense,&nbsp;
the only real difference between the shape&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.460 --> 00:17:36.970
of the graphs is going from here to here&nbsp;
in this rescaling. So, we're rescaling it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:36.970 --> 00:17:42.730
making it wider or narrower, and perhaps&nbsp;
flipping it over. But then after that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:42.730 --> 00:17:45.550
we're not really doing anything to&nbsp;
the shape—we're moving it around,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:46.060 --> 00:17:52.360
translating it, but not changing its shape. So,&nbsp;
all quadratic polynomials have graphs that are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:52.360 --> 00:18:01.570
readily identifiable. You know what a parabola&nbsp;
looks like. The story with cubics and quartics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:01.570 --> 00:18:06.010
and higher poly numbers is much different,&nbsp;
and that's going to be a very interesting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:12.910
aspect—it's an interesting question in algebraic&nbsp;
geometry of what those things look like. But like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:12.910 --> 00:18:18.100
lines, which are pretty predictable, parabolas&nbsp;
are also very predictable, which is good.

00:18:18.100 --> 00:18:26.230
So, to clarify those translates and scalings on&nbsp;
the last slide, let's have a look at an example.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:26.230 --> 00:18:34.540
So, here is the poly number that we've looked at&nbsp;
before: 5 - 3 alpha - 4 alpha squared. And here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:34.540 --> 00:18:38.890
I'm going through the process of completing the&nbsp;
square just so you can see how it looks again in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:38.890 --> 00:18:47.920
this specific case. First, I take the minus 4 out&nbsp;
as a common factor, so I get alpha squared + 3/4&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:55.690
alpha - 5/4, because I've taken a minus 4 out.&nbsp;
And then in here, I look at this term here and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:55.690 --> 00:19:01.660
divide it by 2 to get 3/8, and I square it and&nbsp;
add it, and to keep things the same, I also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:01.660 --> 00:19:09.160
have to subtract it as well. Then, these three&nbsp;
terms here together form (alpha + 3/8) squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.160 --> 00:19:18.760
and these two terms here—well, it would be x -&nbsp;
4, this thing here becomes just 5, and this one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:18.760 --> 00:19:25.870
here is 9/64. If we multiply that by 4, we get&nbsp;
9/16 with a plus sign because there's a minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:25.870 --> 00:19:37.090
there and a minus there. So, when we simplify,&nbsp;
we get -4(alpha + 3/8) all squared + 89/16. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:37.090 --> 00:19:43.480
so how could we graph that from the point of&nbsp;
view of starting with your basic parabola alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:49.870
squared? Now, here I've drawn a more standard kind&nbsp;
of diagram where I've actually plotted points. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:49.870 --> 00:19:58.600
this is the point (1, 1), point (2, 4), point (3,&nbsp;
9), minus 1, 1, minus 2, 4, minus 3, 9. There—our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:58.600 --> 00:20:05.680
standard parabola—a graph of it. Admittedly, not&nbsp;
a very refined graph, but a graph nevertheless.

00:20:06.790 --> 00:20:12.760
Alright, let's do these various steps.&nbsp;
The first step is to multiply by -4. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:19.450
what effect does that have? Well, each of these&nbsp;
points is multiplied by minus 4, and since that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:19.450 --> 00:20:26.620
the y-coordinate is multiplied by minus 4, instead&nbsp;
of plotting (1, 1), we're going to plot (1, -4),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:26.620 --> 00:20:34.510
and instead of plotting (2, 4), we're going to&nbsp;
plot (2, -16). And instead of plotting (3, 9),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:34.510 --> 00:20:39.670
we'd plot (3, -36), but that's off&nbsp;
our page, so we can't see it. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:39.670 --> 00:20:46.690
we just get these few points, and we connect them&nbsp;
up, and then that's our graph of -4 alpha squared.

00:20:46.690 --> 00:20:53.680
The next thing we have to do is to take care&nbsp;
of this shift in here: we're replacing alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:53.680 --> 00:21:02.200
with alpha + 3/8. What does that do to this&nbsp;
thing? Well, it moves it over to the left—it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:02.200 --> 00:21:07.270
a translate to the left. Okay, there's a plus&nbsp;
sign, so you might get confused and think about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:07.270 --> 00:21:12.040
it moving to the right—no, we're moving it&nbsp;
to the left. The graph here is to the left,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:12.040 --> 00:21:20.710
and it's now got its vertex at -3/8. In your mind,&nbsp;
you can check that because the value at -3/8,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:20.710 --> 00:21:27.460
namely here, is going to be zero, so it really&nbsp;
does go through that point there. And otherwise,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:27.460 --> 00:21:32.920
we just take all of these points and move&nbsp;
them over by -3/8 to get that one there.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:42.550
And then the final stage is to add 89/16,&nbsp;
which is just a little bit more than 5. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:42.550 --> 00:21:49.990
we have to add a little more than 5 to each one of&nbsp;
these points, and we obtain this graph—that's our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.990 --> 00:21:59.080
graph of the original polynomial P illustrating&nbsp;
how it comes from alpha squared by a sequence of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:59.080 --> 00:22:04.720
transformations: scaling, then a horizontal&nbsp;
translation, then a vertical translation.

00:22:04.720 --> 00:22:10.030
Now we're going to have a few&nbsp;
more slightly advanced theorems,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:10.030 --> 00:22:18.670
which are often not found in high school courses&nbsp;
or even in first-year or second-year courses at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:18.670 --> 00:22:24.700
uni or college. It's a bit of a shame because&nbsp;
these are natural, easy-to-prove consequences&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:24.700 --> 00:22:30.490
of what we've already done, and I think they're&nbsp;
geometrically interesting facts about parabolas.

00:22:32.740 --> 00:22:38.260
Alright, the first one is that if we&nbsp;
look at tangents to a general parabola&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:38.260 --> 00:22:45.430
or general quadratic polynomial, and those&nbsp;
tangents are at r1 and r2, then the two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:45.430 --> 00:22:53.260
tangents will meet at a point, and here is&nbsp;
an explicit formula for where they meet. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:53.260 --> 00:22:58.360
we'll have a look at the formula, and then we'll&nbsp;
talk about some very interesting aspects of it.

00:22:58.360 --> 00:23:04.030
Okay, so what we're claiming is that if we&nbsp;
look at the two tangent lines—the two tangent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:04.030 --> 00:23:10.570
lines to P at r1 and r2—so here they were.&nbsp;
These are the formulas that we had before,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:10.570 --> 00:23:19.120
with r1 for the first one and with r2 for the&nbsp;
second one—those are the two equations of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:19.120 --> 00:23:24.220
lines. We have to find where they meet, so&nbsp;
we have to use the meet of lines theorem,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:24.220 --> 00:23:28.450
which is a formula that tells us if&nbsp;
we have equations for the two lines&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:28.450 --> 00:23:40.000
or linear polynomial x, where that meet&nbsp;
is—this minus this over this minus this.

00:23:42.490 --> 00:23:48.940
Alright, what is this minus this? Well, the&nbsp;
a's cancel, and we get cr2 squared minus cr1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:48.940 --> 00:23:58.660
squared. And what is this minus this? Well, now&nbsp;
the b's cancel, and we get 2cr2 minus 2cr1. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:58.660 --> 00:24:08.620
the second term, the second coefficient,&nbsp;
is this thing times this one—there it is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:08.620 --> 00:24:15.250
there—minus this times this all over that same&nbsp;
denominator that we had before, this minus this.

00:24:15.250 --> 00:24:22.060
Okay, so then what you do is you expand&nbsp;
these two terms out, and it turns out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:22.060 --> 00:24:28.980
that the numerators in both cases have a factor&nbsp;
of c(r2 - r1), which you can cancel. And this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:28.980 --> 00:24:35.040
thing here becomes (r1 + r2)/2. And then you&nbsp;
can check—some exercise—that when you do the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:35.040 --> 00:24:45.480
expansion and divide by the common factor,&nbsp;
you can get a + b(r1 + r2)/2 + cr1r2. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:45.480 --> 00:24:51.810
the interesting point that answers an exercise&nbsp;
that I gave you in the last video: the last video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:51.810 --> 00:25:00.210
I asked you to explain this phenomenon that&nbsp;
two tangents were meeting above their midpoint.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:00.210 --> 00:25:07.140
And here what we see is this a very general&nbsp;
phenomenon: that the x-coordinate of the meet&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:07.140 --> 00:25:12.900
of these two tangents is always exactly halfway&nbsp;
between the two coordinates. No, it's the average.

00:25:12.900 --> 00:25:19.230
And I should remark about this thing here—it's&nbsp;
also rather pleasant. It has the same form as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:19.230 --> 00:25:25.620
the original polynomial: a + b something + c&nbsp;
something else. And this is a linear thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:25.620 --> 00:25:31.350
and this is a quadratic thing, just like over&nbsp;
here. But here we've got the average of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:31.350 --> 00:25:37.410
two r's, and here we have the product of the&nbsp;
two r's. So, in some sense, it's almost the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:37.410 --> 00:25:43.320
simplest kind of thing that you could cook&nbsp;
up with r1 and r2 sort of involved in here.

00:25:43.320 --> 00:25:51.000
We're going to need one more result about&nbsp;
lines that we didn't talk about last time. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:57.570
this is the theorem that tells us how to find the&nbsp;
equation of a line between two points in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:57.570 --> 00:26:04.980
polynomials. So, if x1 and x2 are distinct, then&nbsp;
the line P equals a + b alpha—in other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:04.980 --> 00:26:14.820
the linear polynomial on which both (x1, y1) and&nbsp;
(x2, y2) lie—is given by these two equations. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:14.820 --> 00:26:20.100
this is the expression for a, and this is the&nbsp;
expression for b. And they have very similar&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:20.100 --> 00:26:30.810
forms to the formula we were just using. The&nbsp;
formula for a is (x1y2 - x2y1)/(x1 - x2),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:30.810 --> 00:26:40.320
and b is (y1 - y2)/(x1 - x2). So,&nbsp;
I remind you that these two numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:40.320 --> 00:26:46.230
represent the y-intercept of the line&nbsp;
as well as the slope of the line. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:46.230 --> 00:26:51.510
this is a relatively familiar formula for the&nbsp;
slope of the line between two points; this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:51.510 --> 00:26:58.050
perhaps a somewhat less familiar formula for&nbsp;
the y-intercept of the line between two points.

00:26:58.050 --> 00:27:07.380
So, what's the proof? Well, we have to solve two&nbsp;
equations. We are trying to find a + b so that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:07.380 --> 00:27:13.950
this point and this point both lie on this&nbsp;
linear polynomial—in other words, y1 equals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:13.950 --> 00:27:22.770
a + bx1 and y2 equals a + bx2. We have to solve&nbsp;
these two linear equations for a and b. That's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:22.770 --> 00:27:27.090
about the level of the exercise. I'll leave you&nbsp;
to do that to find that those are the solutions.

00:27:27.090 --> 00:27:35.400
So, we're going to apply that formula that&nbsp;
we've just proven to have a look at the standard&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:35.400 --> 00:27:43.920
parabola, parabola P equals alpha squared, or&nbsp;
in x and y coordinates, y equals x squared. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:43.920 --> 00:27:49.260
there it is—I've drawn it a little bit freehand&nbsp;
this time. It goes to the point (1, 1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:49.260 --> 00:27:56.100
through the point (2, 4)—it's a very beautiful&nbsp;
curve. And we've chosen two points on it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:56.100 --> 00:28:04.230
a1 and a2, and the x-coordinate here is r1, and&nbsp;
the x-coordinate is r2. So, this point is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:04.230 --> 00:28:12.120
point (r1, r1 squared), and this is the point (r2,&nbsp;
r2 squared). And I'm interested in two things:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:12.120 --> 00:28:17.610
I'm interested in the line that joins those&nbsp;
two points, and I'm also interested in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:17.610 --> 00:28:26.130
two tangents to the parabola at those two points&nbsp;
and where they meet. So, we know where they meet&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:26.130 --> 00:28:32.430
because we've just proven a theorem about that.&nbsp;
And I remind you that they meet at—first of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:32.430 --> 00:28:36.930
the x-coordinate is the average of r1 and&nbsp;
r2, and the y-coordinate here is obtained&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:36.930 --> 00:28:46.260
from the poly number by taking a + b times this&nbsp;
plus c times the product of r1 and r2. Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:46.260 --> 00:28:50.490
this is a very simple form—it only&nbsp;
has the c term, and the c is 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:51.120 --> 00:28:58.170
so we're only getting r1r2 instead of those three&nbsp;
things added up. So, this is the formula for the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:58.170 --> 00:29:07.140
point where the two tangents to the curve&nbsp;
at a1 and a2 meet. And I remarked once again&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:07.140 --> 00:29:13.260
that the x-coordinate here is exactly halfway&nbsp;
between r1 and r2, because it's the average.

00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:23.430
Alright, what about the equation of this line?&nbsp;
Well, we've just proven a formula for that. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:23.430 --> 00:29:31.080
here are the two points. Then, let's say&nbsp;
we say that the line is s + t alpha. Then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:31.080 --> 00:29:35.970
the formula that we just wrote down&nbsp;
was that s is equal to—how do you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:35.970 --> 00:29:46.020
get that?—r1 times r2 squared minus r2&nbsp;
times r1 squared all over r1 - r2. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:46.020 --> 00:29:50.640
here there's a common factor of r1r2,&nbsp;
and the other factor is r2 - r1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:50.640 --> 00:30:02.070
which cancels with r1 - r2, leaving a minus&nbsp;
sign. So, s is -r1r2. And what about t,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:02.070 --> 00:30:11.370
the slope? It's r1 squared minus r2 squared&nbsp;
divided by r1 - r2. Well, that factors immediately&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:11.370 --> 00:30:21.480
as r1 + r2. And so there is the equation for&nbsp;
our line: -r1r2 + (r1 + r2) all times alpha.

00:30:21.480 --> 00:30:32.760
Now, it's a very pleasant relationship—the&nbsp;
relationship between this line and this point. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:32.760 --> 00:30:38.190
in more advanced mathematics—and we'll be talking&nbsp;
a little bit more about this—this is a very, very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:38.190 --> 00:30:46.140
important relationship that somehow characterizes&nbsp;
this conic. Okay, so if we move these two points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:46.140 --> 00:30:51.300
around, and of course this line will move around,&nbsp;
and this point here will also move around. And we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:51.300 --> 00:30:58.980
say that the relationship between this line L&nbsp;
and this point L is an example of polarity. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:58.980 --> 00:31:04.910
we sometimes say that this is the pole of this&nbsp;
line, and we sometimes say that this line is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:04.910 --> 00:31:14.090
polar of this point. We'll talk a little bit more&nbsp;
about that in future videos—that's an important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:14.090 --> 00:31:18.110
concept, so you're seeing it here for the first&nbsp;
time in this simple case of this parabola.

00:31:18.110 --> 00:31:27.140
There are a few more things to point out&nbsp;
here. One is that given this parabola, we can,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:27.140 --> 00:31:36.470
in some sense, find addition and multiplication&nbsp;
geometrically inside here. So, how is that? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:36.470 --> 00:31:48.770
suppose that you have two points, r1 and r2,&nbsp;
on the line, and you wanted to add them. Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:48.770 --> 00:31:58.370
one way of getting that sum, r1 + r2, would be to&nbsp;
take r1 and r2, take the points on the parabola,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:58.370 --> 00:32:07.400
draw this line, and look at its slope. Right, we&nbsp;
know that r1 + r2 is the slope of this line. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:07.400 --> 00:32:11.540
the addition—it's maybe a curious way of&nbsp;
thinking about the addition—can be sort&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:11.540 --> 00:32:19.070
of done geometrically if you can read off&nbsp;
the slope. What about the product? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:19.070 --> 00:32:29.000
you can see a product here. Okay, if you wanted to&nbsp;
find what r1 times r2 was, one way of doing that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:34.850
would be to say, alright, we could take r1, r2,&nbsp;
we can look at the two tangents, and we can see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:34.850 --> 00:32:42.440
where they meet. And then the y-coordinate of that&nbsp;
is going to be r1 times r2. Another way of finding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:42.440 --> 00:32:48.500
the product is to look at this equation here.&nbsp;
There's a product over floating around here. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:48.500 --> 00:32:55.340
what is the significance of this quantity?&nbsp;
It's the y-intercept of this line. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:55.340 --> 00:33:00.950
here's a kind of a curious sort of slide rule—a&nbsp;
parabolic slide rule for multiplication. You want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:00.950 --> 00:33:07.610
to multiply r1 times r2? You just go up to the&nbsp;
parabola, you draw the line, you see where that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:07.610 --> 00:33:17.780
line meets the y-axis—that's, well, not exactly&nbsp;
the product; it's minus the product. So here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:17.780 --> 00:33:25.190
in this case, the product of this one times&nbsp;
this one is pretty close to being minus two. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:25.190 --> 00:33:29.480
both addition and multiplication are somehow&nbsp;
encoded in the geometry of the parabola.

00:33:29.480 --> 00:33:35.720
While we're thinking about these two things,&nbsp;
I'll give you some awesome exercises so you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:42.140
can have some practice thinking about this lovely&nbsp;
geometry. So, the first exercise is very much in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:42.140 --> 00:33:47.150
line with what I've just been talking about. It's&nbsp;
another way of thinking about addition using the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:47.150 --> 00:33:53.240
geometry of this standard parabola. So, I want you&nbsp;
to show that if you're talking about the standard&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:53.240 --> 00:33:57.230
parabola, P equals alpha squared—there&nbsp;
it is—and if you have two points on it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:57.230 --> 00:34:03.980
just as before, a1 at a2, now up here with&nbsp;
coordinate r1 here and coordinate r2 here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:03.980 --> 00:34:13.730
and let's just denote the vertex by O for&nbsp;
origin—that's got coordinates (0, 0)—then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:13.730 --> 00:34:19.910
if you do the following: if you take the line&nbsp;
through the origin, which is parallel to a1a2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:19.910 --> 00:34:27.170
okay, that's the meaning of this—it's parallel to&nbsp;
here; it means it has the same slope—okay, then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:27.170 --> 00:34:33.770
you find out where it meets the parabola in the&nbsp;
second point. Then that x-coordinate there will be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:33.770 --> 00:34:41.930
r1 + r2. It's another way of geometrically adding&nbsp;
two numbers using the geometry of the parabola.

00:34:41.930 --> 00:34:53.210
This second exercise is a very lovely and&nbsp;
important fact: that if A lies on the polar of B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:53.210 --> 00:35:00.920
then B lies on the polar of A. Okay, so&nbsp;
here's a general parabola—it doesn't need&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:00.920 --> 00:35:05.810
to be the standard parabola, this works for a&nbsp;
general parabola. So, you have a parabola here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:05.810 --> 00:35:13.550
and you have a point A, and that point A has&nbsp;
a polar line—this one here. And I remind you,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:13.550 --> 00:35:18.470
what that means is that if you draw the&nbsp;
tangents to the parabola at the places&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:18.470 --> 00:35:24.860
where the line meets it, you get two. So, that's&nbsp;
the polar of A. And there's another point B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:24.860 --> 00:35:30.740
and here in green is its polar. So, if you&nbsp;
take the places where the green line meets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:30.740 --> 00:35:36.410
the parabola and draw the tangents, you get&nbsp;
two. Okay, the statement is that if A lies on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:36.410 --> 00:35:46.970
the polar of B—which in this case it does—then B&nbsp;
lies on the polar of A. This is a general fact—you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:46.970 --> 00:35:51.410
can prove it just for the standard parabola.&nbsp;
Those of you with a bit more algebraic skills,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:51.980 --> 00:35:56.000
try to see if you can do it for a&nbsp;
general parabola. Excellent exercise.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:36:05.030
And the third exercise relates again a chord of&nbsp;
the parabola and the meet of the two tangents down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:05.030 --> 00:36:10.910
here. So, if this point here has x-coordinate&nbsp;
r1, and this point has x-coordinate r2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:10.910 --> 00:36:17.600
then we know that where these two tangents meet,&nbsp;
that's going to have x-coordinate (r1 + r2)/2—the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:18.230 --> 00:36:25.790
average of r1 and r2, or the place halfway between&nbsp;
them. And now the exercise is to have a look at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:25.790 --> 00:36:33.710
the corresponding point on the parabola with the&nbsp;
same x-coordinate. So, you just go vertically up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:33.710 --> 00:36:39.020
or down until you hit the parabola—you get&nbsp;
a point. And the claim is that if you look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:39.020 --> 00:36:45.200
at the tangent line at that point, it's going&nbsp;
to be parallel to the line joining a1 and a2.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:45.200 --> 00:36:55.310
This is not necessarily horizontal, right? It&nbsp;
could be anywhere depending on the chord a1a2.

00:36:58.220 --> 00:37:03.230
Alright, those are three excellent exercises&nbsp;
that will get you really appreciating the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:03.230 --> 00:37:08.480
geometry of the parabola, and I hope&nbsp;
starting to appreciate the fact that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:08.480 --> 00:37:14.480
we're doing mathematics and we're doing calculus,&nbsp;
and even though our origins were very elementary,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:14.480 --> 00:37:19.580
it seemed as if we did almost no work, and&nbsp;
suddenly calculus popped up in front of us.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:19.580 --> 00:37:25.580
This should be disorienting to mathematics&nbsp;
educators—if you're a mathematics educator&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:25.580 --> 00:37:29.300
out there, have a think about this,&nbsp;
have a good long think about it.

00:37:29.300 --> 00:37:37.400
Next time, we're going to go up a step&nbsp;
to talking about cubics. I'm going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:37.400 --> 00:37:44.270
apply our reasoning about tangents and&nbsp;
derivatives to study cubic equations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:44.270 --> 00:37:50.120
which are a fabulous world of all kinds&nbsp;
of interesting things about cubics. We're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:50.120 --> 00:37:54.980
going to make some contact with that. I'm&nbsp;
going to show you the prettiest theorem that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:54.980 --> 00:38:00.590
I know in calculus, and you will not have&nbsp;
seen it before, so it will be a real treat.

00:38:01.280 --> 00:38:01.970
Alright, so next time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:01.970 --> 00:38:06.890
the prettiest theorem in calculus and&nbsp;
cubics. I hope you'll join me for that.

00:38:06.890 --> 00:38:10.250
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

